</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-80_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-81_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-82_ pf-heading-1-h3">Conclusion
</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-84_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Febrile convulsions in children and babies can be distressing, but with prompt and appropriate first aid, the situation can be managed effectively. By staying calm, protecting the child, and seeking medical advice when necessary, caregivers can ensure the safety and well-being of young ones experiencing febrile convulsions.



